A day before Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) Commander in Chief Julius Malema appears in court, some of the party&#8217;s leaders were spotted at a Universal Church in Thaba Nchu &#8220;getting blessings&#8221;. Pictures doing the rounds on Twitter show some of the party&#8217;s leaders, among them Mandisa Mashego, Fana Mokoena and Veronica Mente, with EFF members, being prayed for at the church. While Mashego and Mokoena were in casual clothes, other EFF members could be seen in the party&#8217;s regalia, while some wore military clothes. @veronica_mente @MandisaMashego @fanamokoena @EFFSouthAfrica EFF leaders getting blessings from Universal church Thaba Nchu pic.twitter.com/ZC02gPogEh &mdash; Skhumbuzo Sibanda (@jskhumba) November 13, 2016 Malema is expected to appear on Monday in the Bloemfontein Regional Court. This after AfriForum complained against Malema in December 2014 in terms of the Prevention of Illegal Eviction from and Unlawful Occupation of Land Act, stating it was illegal for a person to occupy land without the permission of the owner or person in charge of the land. The complaint came after he encouraged his supporters at an EFF conference in Bloemfontein to occupy land nationwide. We are going to occupy the unoccupied land because we need the land, Malema reportedly told the gathering. For us to eat we must have the land. For us to work we must have the land. I come from Seshego. If there is unoccupied land we will go and occupy the land with my branch. You must go and do the same in the branch where you come from. Speaking to EFF membersinat Newcastle last week, Malema said nothing was going to stop him from demanding land. &#8220;If it means I must go to prison for telling you to occupy land, then let it. I&#8217;d rather go to jail for land,&#8221; he said. He further told the crowd that he would rather go to jail for land than fir corruption, as &#8220;land is who we are!&#8221; &#8220;They found peaceful Africans when they came here! They slaughtered them! We are here to demand our peace [of] land. &#8220;We are here to restore your comfort! We thank even those who are here from the ANC to demand land.&#8221; He said the law they had used to charge him in Newcastle, the Riotous Assemblies Act of 1956, had been passed by the apartheid government in reaction to the adoption of the Freedom Charter, and was the same law used to put Nelson Mandela, who later became democratic South Africa&#8217;s first president, in jail. &#8220;Let the court declare publicly that we blacks don&#8217;t have the right to land, and we&#8217;ll fight it! Nothing will silence us!&#8221; Additional reporting by Amanda Watson